Message::/itemRef : ItemDefintion [0..1] = self
SequenceFlow::/conditionExpression : BPMNExpression = ControlFloe.guard (defined on Activity edge)

SequenceFlow::/targetRef : ActivityNode = ControlFlow.target (defined on Activity edge). Constrained to elements stereotyped by BPMN Flow Node stereotypes

Would be good to abstract out the commonalities, instead of defining new associations each time the way BPMN does.' />
<ownedComment xmi:type='uml:Comment' xmi:id='_17_0_8740266_1292845589309_39311_3197' body='BPMN::DataStore/Ref is persistent, so can't be based on any of the UML::ObjectNodes, including DataStoreNode so. Persistence in UML is usually handled with the StructuralFeatureActions. Will need to come up with something here. ' />
<ownedComment xmi:type='uml:Comment' xmi:id='_17_0_8740266_1292923840646_871974_2227' body='DataInput and DataOutput for Processes can be based on UML::ActivityParameterNode, Pin, or Parameter, depending on whether the containing DataInputOutputSpecification is owned by a BPMN::Process, Activity, or GlobalTask, respectively. ActivityParameterNode requires a UML::Parameter, which BPMN doesn't have separately from Data IO, but we can require parameters be created in UML. isCollection is a problem again, it means the type is a collection of the ItemDefinition. If we keep BPMNActivity::dataInputs/Outputs, it can be derived from the parameters of the activity. ' />
<ownedComment xmi:type='uml:Comment' xmi:id='_17_0_8740266_1296045824077_946111_2684' body='We can omit Pool. It's the name of the notation used for Participants.' />
<ownedComment xmi:type='uml:Comment' xmi:id='_17_0_8740266_1297167425333_44949_3933' body='Ask BPMNers about methodology for linking process DataIn(Out)put operation input / output. They said the methodology isn't specified, but it's generally expected processes will have events to receive the operations specified in their (participant's) interfaces.
' /> <ownedComment xmi:type='uml:Comment' xmi:id='_17_0_8740266_1297184084715_841973_2477' body='CB: BPMN InputOutputSpecification is owned by either BPMN Activities or CallableElements, so IOSpec corresponds to the collection of UML pins (when on BPMN Activity) or UML Parameters / ActivityParameterNodes (when on BPMN CallableElement). BPMN IOSpecs own DataInput and DataOutput. BPMN DataIn(out)Put is based on UML In(Out)putPin and ActivityParameterNode (which refers to UML Parameters). BPMN DataIn(Out)put in Activity IOSpecs do not have a BPMN notation, whereas UML pins do. BPMN DataIn(Out)put in Processes are notated as document symbols with arrows in them. Profile will not have BPMN IOSpec. CB: BPMN IOSpecs on CallActivity and the called Process must be exact copies of each other. There is no association between these, they are matched because the IOSpecs are the same. UML pins don't need to be exactly the same as the called behavior parameters.' />
